  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 9
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 9
  levelTerms:
  - level: 35
    terms:
    - term: Fluid
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Any substance that characterizes flow, no rigid structure and
        conforms to the shape
      details: Blaise Pascal noted in one (1) of his studies that pressure applied
        to a fluid in a closed container is transmitted equally to every point of
        the fluid and the walls of the container. This is essentially proven to be
        true and is now called Pascal's principle.
    - term: 'Density '
      unit: p
      type: 1
      description: Amount of mass m per unit volume V of a substance
      details: "The density of the liquid. Hence, the locations deeper than point
        A experience more pressure, and those shallower than point A experience less
        pressure.\n\nDensity: \u03C1 = m/V\n"
    - term: 'Specific Gravity '
      unit: g_sp
      type: 2
      description: Ratio of fluids density compared to standard fluid density
      details: "For liquids, the standard density (pst) used is water, whose density
        is 1 g/cm3. For gases, the standard density is air (i.e., a mixture of various
        elemental and compound gases), whose density is 1.29 g/L.\r\n\nDensity: \u03C1
        = m/V\n\nSpecific Gravity:\ng_sp = \u03C1/\u03C1_st\n\nPressure: P = F/A"
    - term: 'Pressure '
      unit: P
      type: 2
      description: "Unit is Pa or N/m\xB2"
      details: "This property is similar to another concept in our previous lesson.
        For solids, this is called stress. The units of pressure are Pa or N/m2(1
        Pa = 1 N/m2 or 1kg /m s2), dyne/cm2, or any similar unit with the same dimension.
        Another frequently used unit of pressure is the atmosphere(atm).\n\nPressure:
        P = F/A\n\n\u03C1 = pressure\n\u03C1_st = standard density used in water\n"
    - term: 'Viscosity '
      unit: "\u03B7"
      type: 1
      description: Measure how it resists flowing
      details: "Viscosity (n, Greek letter \"eta\") is the measure of how it resists
        flowing. Physically, it is the ratio of shearing stress (r) to the velocity
        gradient in a fluid. Liquids such as water and cooking oil flow easily because
        of their low viscosity, while thick fluids such as honey and condensed milk
        tend to resist flowing. The unit of viscosity is pascal-second (Pa \u22C5
        s), but it is rarely used in the scientific community, preferring the Poise
        [pronounced pwahz] (P) and the dyne-s/ cm2 over it. The unit Poise is named
        in honor of the French physiologist Jean Poiseuille. Ten (10) poise is equal
        to one (1) Pa \u22C5 s, making the centipoise (cP) equal to a millipascal-second
        (mPa \u22C5s).\n\n\n"
